definition.value: An aldonic acid phosphate that is D-xylonic acid carrying a single phosphate group at the 5-position.
An alpha-D-galactoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a disaccharide consisting of alpha-D-glucosyl and alpha-D-galactosyl residues linked (1->4).

A beta-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a tetrasaccharide consisting of alpha-D-glucosyl, alpha-D-galactosyl, beta-D-glucuronosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues linked sequentially (1->4).
A 4-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of 5-phospho-D-xylonic acid. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A aldonolactone phosphate that is D-xylono-1,4-lactone carrying a single phospho substituent at position 5.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of D-xylono-1,4-lactone-5-phosphate. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A aldonolactone phosphate that is L-arabino-1,4-lactone carrying a single phospho substituent at position 5.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of L-arabino-1,4-lactone-5-phosphate. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An arabinonic acid derivative that is L-arabinonic acid carrying a single phospho substituent at position 5.
A tetrapeptide obtained by formal condensation of the C-terminal carboxy group of Ac-Tyr-Val-Ala-Asp with the amino group of 7-amino-4-trifluoromethylcoumarin.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of 5-phospho-L-arabinonic acid. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A (3S)-hydroxyacyl-CoA arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any long-chain (3S)-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any long-chain 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroidal acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of (22E)-3-oxo-chola-4,22-dien-24-oyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A (3S)-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any short-chain (3S)-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of C-terminal-gamma-(L-glutamyl 5-semialdehyde)-L-2-glutamic acid group. Major structure at pH 7.3.
An alpha-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a disaccharide consisting of a beta- and an alpha-D-glucosyl residue linked (1->4).

An alpha-amino-acid residue anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups as well as protonatoin of the amino group of C-terminal-gamma-(L-ornithyl)-L-2-glutamic acid group. Major structure at pH 7.3.
An alpha-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a trisaccharide consisting of  beta-D-glucosyl, alpha-D-glucosyl and alpha-D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->4).
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-alpha-phenylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-L-alpha-phenylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A dihydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is octadecanoic acid in which the two hydroxy groups are located at positions 9R and 10S.
A brassinosteroid that is 24-epi-cathasterone on which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 22 has been replaced by a sulfo group.
A class of glycoglycerolipids that consists of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol having an (alpha-D-galactopyranosyl)-(1->2)-(alpha-D-glucopyranosyl) glycosyl moiety attached at position 3.
A cholestanoid that zymosterol in which the two methyl groups at positions 26 and 27 have been replaced by a  cyclopropane ring.
An S-substituted glutathione in which the thiol hydrogen of glutathoine has been replaced by a 6-methylthiohexylhydroximoyl group.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 5 has been replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A 3-(3-sn-phosphatidyl)-sn-glycerol 1-phosphate in which both phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl).
A beta-D-glucoside that is beta-D-glucopyranose in which the anomeric hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a 1-naphthyl group.

An alpha-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a tetrasaccharide consisting of two beta-D-glucosyl residues, an alpha-D-glucosyl residue and (at the reducing end) an alpha-D-galactosyl residue, all linked sequentially (1->4).
A dipeptide that is cysteinylglycine in which the thiol hydrogen has been replaced by a 4-hydroxy-1-oxononan-3-yl group.
A quercetin O-glycoside in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 of quercetin has been replaced by a gentiobiosyl group.

An alpha-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a pentasaccharide consisting of  alpha-D-galactosyl, beta-D-glucuronosyl, beta-D-glucosyl, alpha-D-glucosyl and alpha-D-galactosyl residues, all linked sequentially (1->4).
A quercetin O-glycoside in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 of quercetin has been replaced by a gentiotriosyl group.

An alpha-D-glucoside that is the 2-aminoethyl glycoside of a hexasaccharide consisting of alpha-D-glucosyl, alpha-D-galactosyl, beta-D-glucuronosyl, beta-D-glucosyl, alpha-D-glucosyl and alpha-D-galactosyl residues, all linked sequentially (1->4).
A 3-(4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-ylidene)pyruvate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3-[(1Z,4R)-4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-ylidene]pyruvic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A tetrahydro-4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3-[(1R,4R)-4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-yl]pyruvic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A tetrahydro-4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3-[(1S,4R)-4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-yl]pyruvic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A kaempferol O-glucoside in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 of kaempferol has been replaced by a gentiobiosyl group.
A phosphatidylglycerol (18:1/16:1) in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and (3E)-hexadecenoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylglycerol in which the two acyl groups contain 34 carbon atoms and 3 double bonds.
A phosphatidylglycerol 34:3 in which the acyl group at position 1 contains 18 carbons and two double bonds while that at position 2 contains 16 carbons and 1 double bond.
A phosphatidylglycerol (18:2/16:1) in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as linoleoyl and (3E)-hexadecenoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylglycerol in which the two acyl groups contain 34 carbon atoms and 4 double bonds.
A phosphatidylglycerol 36:1 in which the acyl group at position 1 contains 18 carbons and 3 double bonds while that at position 2 contains 16 carbons and 1 double bond.
A phosphatidylglycerol (18:3/16:1) in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as alpha-linolenoyl and (3E)-hexadecenoyl respectively.
A monogalactosyldiacylglycerol 34:4 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and (7Z,10Z,13Z)-hexadecatrienoyl respectively.
A 3-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are both specified as alpha-linolenoyl.
A 3-[alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl]-1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are both specified as linoleoyl.
